observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed that the –
a) Municipal Accountant (i) record all inventories upon receipt, including those received through donations; and (ii) record the necessary adjustments to recognize and correct the understatement of inventories amounting to ₱5,527,437.76 in the accounting records;
b) GSO (i) furnish the RHU with the Purchase Order upon delivery of health commodities, to enable proper encoding in the eLMIS; and (ii) institute control measures to ensure the submission of all Requisition and Issue Slips from all issuing offices;
c) MSWDO ensure that all welfare goods received and distributed are properly documented through Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS), stock cards or inventory logs, and other inventory monitoring forms; and
d) Inventory Committee to consistently prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) on a semestral basis.

a. Municipal Accountant to properly record the Cash Advance to Advances to Special Disbursing Officer;

b. Municipal Accountant ensure that the submission of supporting documents is made within the 7-day required timeline;

c. Administrative Officer V from the Office of the Municipal Mayor to fully liquidate all the cash advance for CF at year-end; and
d. The Municipal Treasurer ensure that the SDO’s signature is affixed in the documentation prior to the release of cash/check.

We recommended and  Management agreed  to  

a) strictly comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2012-002 for the timely submission of the utilization report of LDRRM Fund to the Auditor every 15th day of each month for the timely review and verification; and 

b) ensure completeness of the supporting documents attached to disbursement vouchers as mandated by Section 4(6) of PD 1445 and COA Circular 2012-001 under the General Requirements for All types of Disbursements;

We recommended that Management:

(a)  through the MENRO, adopt policies and strategies to meet the target goal of the Municipality in waste diversion;

(b) ensure full implementation/operation of the existing seventeen 17 barangay’s MRF to help in waste diversion of the Municipality and if feasible for the remaining 12 barangays to establish their own MRFs; 

(c)   continue all its efforts and initiative in maintaining the operations of the centralized MRF and the implementation of its plans and programs incorporated in its 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan in accordance with the RA No. 9003.

We recommended Management 

(a) xxx;

(b)  prioritize the filling-up of the LDRRMO III and LDRRMO II position in the MDRRMO to fully capacitate the office and to strengthen its function; 

(c)  xxx; and 

(d) observe strictly the provisions of (i) Section 4 (6) and Section 100 of Presidential Decree No. 1445; (ii) Section 4.1 of COA Circular 97-002; and (iii) GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020.

We also recommended that LDRRM Officer comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2012-002 for the preparation and submission of the utilization report of LDRRM Fund to the Auditor every 15th day of each month for timely review and verification thereof.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation that the: 

(a) Local Chief Executive (i) require the inventory committee to conduct a complete annual physical inventory of PPE by type, with the end view of establishing the correctness of the reported balances as well as the existence, condition and custodianship of the municipal assets and submit the RPCPPE not later than January 31 of each year to enable reconciliation with the accounting and property records and correction of verified discrepancies; and 

(ii) allot funds and assigned a focal person that will focus in securing land titles of the land holdings owned by the LGU without Transfer Certificates of Title; 

(b) OIC-GSO prepare and maintain updated property cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report; 

(c) Municipal Accountant (i) maintain updated PPELC; and

We commended the Municipality’s effort for the compliance with some of the requirements of RA No. 9003 such as approval of the 10-Year Solid Waste Management Plan and with the mandatory segregation at source.

We recommended and Management agreed to:  

(a) strictly comply on the required composition of SWMB for proper representation thereof; 


(b) require the  remaining 28 Barangays who failed to established their MRF to comply with the Act and ensure proper waste disposal within their respective area;

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9003 on the prescribed composition for an efficient SWMB and establishment of functional disposal facility; 

(b) enjoin and support the barangay officials to establish their own or clustered composting and recycling of waste facility and to implement waste segregation at source.
